            "answer_text": "No. How exactly could Napoleon Bonaparte offer something that he never possessed and would never possess? The Peacock Throne was originally commissioned by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in 1635. It was taken by Nadir Shah during his plunder of Delhi in 1739. The throne was taken to Persia, along with the rest of the riches. On 19 June 1747, Nader Shah was assassinated by those close to him. Here the Peacock Throne disappears from history. It was probably broken apart or destroyed during the chaos following the assassination of Nader Shah. The pieces and jewels were probably taken as loot. Napoleon was not even born at this time when the Peacock Throne was destroyed. How could he offer something that no longer even existed? Another thing to note is that most of Nader Shah\u2019s sons and grandsons were executed by Adel Shah, Nader\u2019s successor and nephew. This too was before Napoleon was born.  The Peacock Throne ",
